{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-01-07T23:33:44.268829+00:00", "modified": "2026-01-07T23:33:44.956696+00:00", "id": 18177671, "conceptrecid": "18177670", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177671", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177670", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18177671", "metadata": {"title": "One Biosecurity: a unified concept to integrate human, animal, plant, and environmental health", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18177671", "publication_date": "2020", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the IPBES Invasive Alien Species Assessment) In the wake of the SARS-CoV-2 pandemic, the world has woken up to the importance of biosecurity and the need to manage international borders. Yet strong sectorial identities exist within biosecurity that are associated with specific international standards, individual economic interests, specific research communities, and unique stakeholder involvement. Despite considerable research addressing human, animal, plant, and environmental health, the science connections between these sectors remain quite limited. One Biosecurity aims to address these limitations at global, national, and local scales. It is an interdisciplinary approach to biosecurity policy and research that builds on the interconnections between human, animal, plant, and environmental health to effectively prevent and mitigate the impacts of invasive alien species. It provides an integrated perspective to address the many biosecurity risks that transcend the traditional boundaries of health, agriculture, and the environment. Individual invasive alien plant and animal species often have multiple impacts across sectors: as hosts of zoonotic parasites, vectors of pathogens, pests of agriculture or forestry, as well as threats to biodiversity and ecosystem function. It is time these risks were addressed in a systematic way. One Biosecurity is essential to address several major sociological and environmental challenges to biosecurity: climate change, increasing urbanisation, agricultural intensification, human global mobility, loss of technical capability as well as public resistance to pesticides and vaccines. One Biosecurity will require the bringing together of taxonomists, population biologists, modellers, economists, chemists, engineers, and social scientists to engage in a new agenda that is shaped by politics, legislation, and public perceptions.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "MacLeod, Alan", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Spence, Nicola", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Hulme, Philip E.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 1", "Chapter 5", "Chapter 6", "Glossary", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/ce5f45cfa7177e8fb3321e9618cd2704", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/0dbe1d3fe547dad08cb8dc5dcd3398d7bf95d41f349a132d847a054439cc684f", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/2352922/items/CFXAKMXQ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/2352922/items/CFXAKMXQ", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/ce70b5d4c9c9cbdf0ea6b8adada8657e!/b67691-69933", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/359bd494433933b868f85e88d3437f76", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.1042/ETLS20200067", "relation": "isVariantFormOf", "resource_type": "publication", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7430682", "relation": "isCitedBy", "resource_type": "publication-report", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "5", "pages": 